\begin_layout Section*
Wavelet filter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The wavelet transform is commonly used in modern signal-processing applications.
 This type of wavelet filter applies the 
\emph on
Ã  trous
\emph default
 algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Starck2002,Izeddin2012"

\end_inset

 which is an undecimated scheme in which the filter responses are up-sampled,
 thereby inserting holes (
\emph on
trous
\emph default
 in French) between the filter coefficients.
 The output of each filter level, therefore, contains the same number of
 samples as the input.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first step of the filtering is based on separable 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
href{Convolution.html}{convolution}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to obtain the smoothed approximations 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V_{f}=\left(V_{f-1}*\boldsymbol{k}_{f}\right)*\boldsymbol{k}_{f}^{\top}\,,\label{eq:wavelet-approx}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}=I$
\end_inset

 is the input image, 
\begin_inset Formula $f=1,\ldots,N$
\end_inset

 are the levels, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{k}_{f}=\left[k_{1,f},k_{2,f},\ldots,k_{l,f}\right]$
\end_inset

 is a filter kernel at the corresponding level, and 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 is the kernel size.
 The number of levels is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The wavelet transform of the input data at level 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is computed as the difference between two consecutive approximation levels
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{f}=V_{f-1}-V_{f}\,.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This expression acts as a band-pass filter, therefore each wavelet level
 corresponds to a different range of spatial frequencies.
 The first level 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}$
\end_inset

 contains mainly the high spatial frequencies present in the input image
 including noise.
 Higher levels contain ranges of lower and lower image frequency components.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our case, the output of the wavelet filter is the second wavelet level
 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The standard deviation of values obtained in the first wavelet level 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}$
\end_inset

 can be used as a threshold in the filtered image for an approximate localizatio
n of molecules 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Izeddin2012"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The wavelet filter uses a convolution kernel based on normalized B-spline
 basis functions
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Starck2002,Izeddin2012"

\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

-th B-spline basis function of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\mathbb{N}^{+}$
\end_inset

 in the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, written as 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{j,q}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

, is defined recursively as follows.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $q=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
B_{j,1}\left(t\right)=\begin{cases}
1 & \quad\mathrm{if}\; t_{j}\leq t<t_{j+1}\,,\\
0 & \quad\mathrm{otherwise}\,,
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and for 
\begin_inset Formula $q>1$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
B_{j,q}\left(t\right)=\frac{t-t_{j}}{t_{j+q-1}-t_{j}}B_{j,q-1}\left(t\right)+\frac{t_{j+q}-t}{t_{j+q}-t_{j+1}}B_{j+1,q-1}\left(t\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{j,q}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 has non-zero values in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{j}\leq t<t_{j+q}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the first wavelet level, the convolution kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{k}_{1}$
\end_inset

 in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:wavelet-approx"

\end_inset

 is composed from values 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{i,1}\left(x\mid q,s\right)=aB_{0,q}\left(\frac{x}{s}+\frac{q}{2}\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\ldots,l$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x=i-\left(l+1\right)/2$
\end_inset

, the kernel size 
\begin_inset Formula $l=2\left\lceil \frac{qs}{2}\right\rceil -1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $s>0$
\end_inset

 is a sampling factor, and 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a constant scaling factor such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}k_{i,1}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Kernels for higher wavelet levels are obtained by inserting zeros between
 the kernel coefficients.
 Users need to input the degree 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 of the B-spline basis function and the sampling factor 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our implementation, the default kernel uses a B-spline basis function
 of the third degree with a sampling factor 
\begin_inset Formula $s=2$
\end_inset

.
 These settings yield kernels 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{k}_{1}=\left[\frac{1}{16},\frac{1}{4},\frac{3}{8},\frac{1}{4},\frac{1}{16}\right]^{\top}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{k}_{2}=\left[\frac{1}{16},0,\frac{1}{4},0,\frac{3}{8},0,\frac{1}{4},0,\frac{1}{16}\right]^{\top}$
\end_inset

, as suggested in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Starck2002,Izeddin2012"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

